President Joe Biden and Japanese Prime Minister Kishida Fumio met in San Francisco to discuss global and regional security issues, as well as bilateral security and economic cooperation. They condemned Hamas and reaffirmed Israel's right to defend itself, calling for adherence to international humanitarian law. The leaders agreed to provide urgent assistance to civilians in Gaza and to work together to prevent the conflict from spreading, aiming for a political solution and durable peace. They also expressed support for Ukraine's democratic independence and discussed maintaining peace in the Taiwan Strait, the Korean Peninsula, and the East and South China Seas. The leaders committed to close coordination in their diplomacy with China and to advancing their vision for a free and open Indo-Pacific. Additionally, they agreed to accelerate trilateral cooperation with South Korea and highlighted progress on economic cooperation, including the Indo-Pacific Economic Framework for Prosperity and the U.S.-Japan Economic Policy Consultative Committee.